  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      For stage Ib2-IIa2 cervical cancer patients, neoadjuvant therapy followed by radical
      hysterectomy and pelvic lymphadenectomy is one of the managements. Post-operative concurrent
      chemo-radiotherapy is necessary if the patients have high-risk factors, including positive
      surgical margin, parametrium and pelvic nodes. Our previous retrospective study showed that
      combination of neoadjuvant chemotherapy and brachytherapy reduced the proportion of
      post-operative concurrent chemo-radiotherapy compared to neoadjuvant chemotherapy alone.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
  <detailed_description>
    <textblock>
      In the present study, the patients with stage Ib2-IIa2 cervical cancer will receive either
      neoadjuvant chemo/brachytherapy or neoadjuvant chemotherapy before radical hysterectomy and
      pelvic+/- para-aortic lymph node dissection. According to the surgical findings,
      post-operative chemo-radiotherapy will be performed.
    </textblock>
  </detailed_description>
